might have been cause for an <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">Editor</ENAMEX>'s Note pointing out that while some
<ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">people</ENAMEX> may have taken offense, none was intended. But there's no excuse for
censoring <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">cartoonists</ENAMEX> (even after the fact) because they've used religion as
their subject matter. That's like saying <ENAMEX TYPE="WORK_OF_ART">Peanuts</ENAMEX> can't focus on
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Christmas</TIMEX>, or that when <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Brenda Starr</ENAMEX> prays, she can't use language from the
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Lord</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="EVENT">Prayer</ENAMEX>. Since there was no mockery in the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Rugrats</ENAMEX> depiction of
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Kaddish</ENAMEX>-- just one <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">toddler</ENAMEX>'s curiosity -- one can only
conclude the <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">callers</ENAMEX> deemed the comic strip, as a medium, insufficiently
dignified for serious <ENAMEX TYPE="NATIONALITY">Jewish</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">subjects</ENAMEX>. That would be news to <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Art Spiegelman</ENAMEX>,
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">creator</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Maus</ENAMEX> --comic-book accounts of the <ENAMEX TYPE="EVENT">Holocaust</ENAMEX> .
            

